Subject: Compare against origin/release in startup banner update check

Upstream's `hermes_cli/banner.py` runs its own update-availability check
that prints "Update available: N commits behind" on every CLI invocation.
The check hardcodes `origin/main` at three call sites:

  - `_check_via_local_git()` line 167:
      git rev-list --count HEAD..origin/main
  - `get_git_banner_state()` line 308:
      _git_short_hash(repo_dir, "origin/main")
  - `get_git_banner_state()` line 316:
      git rev-list --count origin/main..HEAD

This is a separate code path from `_cmd_update_*` (fixed by
0009-update-default-branch-release.patch). The banner runs unconditionally
on startup; cmd_update runs only when the user types `argo update`.

For an argo customer who installed via the patched install.sh (which
clones `release` per 0006-install-default-branch-release.patch) and whose
`argo update` resolves to `release` per patch 0009, the banner's
`origin/main` reference points at the workshop branch — a completely
different history that contains M-series shepherd loops, build-tool
patches, refactors, etc. that never propagate to `release` until a tag
fires `.github/workflows/release.yml`.

The customer-facing symptom (observed on v2026.5.29 fresh install in
ubuntu:22.04, 2026-05-29):

  $ argo --version
  Argo Agent v0.14.1 (2026.5.29)
  Update available: 108 commits behind — run 'argo update'

  $ argo update --check
  → Fetching from origin...
  ✓ Already up to date.

Customer sees "108 commits behind", runs `argo update`, gets "Already
up to date" — confusing contradiction that undermines trust in the
update mechanism. The bug is in the banner, not in cmd_update.

Same fix as patch 0009: literal swap `main` → `release` at the three
call sites. argo's customer surface lives on `release`; the banner
should compare against the branch the customer's install actually tracks.

Developers who install via `curl ... | bash -s -- --branch main` still
see incorrect banner counts; they can ignore them (the cmd_update
override `argo update --branch main` is the dev workflow).

A future patch may switch banner.py to detect the current branch
dynamically via `git symbolic-ref --short HEAD`, removing the
literal-swap trade-off entirely; for now the literal swap matches
the established 0006 + 0009 pattern.

IU-FR-7, IU-FR-8 (banner consistency with cmd_update target branch).

